{"clauses":[{"item_alias":"K1","response":"The criticism conflates the conceptual mechanism with a specific experimental parameterization. The 'mechanism' field states the general causal condition in falsifiable form: a fixed critic cannot distinguish low-error questions (false-positive risk) from high-error questions (true-positive opportunity) ex ante because it observes candidates rather than the true answer, so its false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds true-positive gains on high-error questions. The measurable quantities (k=7, e~0.10/e~0.35) are pre-registered in the decisive experiment described in prose_notes, and the forbidden cases supply the refutation conditions: case 1 fixes k=5 and e in [0.05,0.45] to test the fixed-critic arm, and case 3 randomizes the adaptivity signal to show the mechanism requires genuine informativeness. The criticism's reading of case 2 as 'internally contradictory' mischaracterizes the schema: case 2 is the predicted positive outcome for the adaptive arm and is listed as a forbidden case precisely because it operationalizes what would have to hold for the claim to survive — it is the complement of the falsifier in case 1, not a contradiction. Case 4 is tagged out of scope because it tests a homogeneous distribution that the claim explicitly excludes; it is not offered as an in-scope refutation condition. Clause (2) is therefore satisfied by cases 1 and 3, which are in-scope, parameterized, and falsifiable without requiring precision/recall pre-registration (the claim concerns whether any fixed precision/recall can beat self-consistency, so the falsifier is the observed harness-vs-self-consistency score gap, not a pre-registered precision/recall bound)."}]}